  "prompt": "How do touchscreens work?",
  "response": "Touchscreens work through several different technologies, but the most common types are:\n\n1. Capacitive Touchscreens:\n- Use the electrical properties of the human body\n- A layer stores electrical charge\n- When a finger touches the screen, it disrupts the electrical field\n- Sensors detect the exact location of the touch\n- Found in most modern smartphones and tablets\n\n2. Resistive Touchscreens:\n- Have two electrically conductive layers separated by a small gap\n- When pressed, the layers connect and complete an electrical circuit\n- Determine touch location based on the point of contact\n- Often used in older devices, ATMs, and industrial equipment\n\n3. Infrared Touchscreens:\n- Use a grid of infrared light beams across the screen surface\n- When something interrupts the beams, the touch location is calculated\n- Can work with any object, not just fingers\n\n4. Surface Acoustic Wave (SAW) Touchscreens:\n- Use ultrasonic waves across the screen surface\n- Touch disrupts these waves, allowing location detection\n- Provides good image clarity\n\nEach technology has different strengths and is suited to different applications based on precision, durability, and cost.",
